description: {"blocks":[{"key":"65fis","text":"Palaeobotanical microfossil analyses are often used to reconstruct palaeoecological histories and past environmental change. To do so, many researchers use lake sediment, for which chronological ordering of stratigraphical layers is possible. Lakes accumulate microfossils including pollen, starch grains, diatoms and phytoliths. Diatom and phytolith assemblages allow inference of vegetation, pH, salinity, water chemistry, and environmental temperature, among others. As an example, we employ this method to study the correlation between palaeobotanical microfossils and desert lake history from Nevada. The preliminary results hint at a complex climatic and environmental variance. Here we propose a protocol split into seven sections to isolate diatoms and phytoliths. By following the protocol, one can prepare samples for microfossil identification and interpretation. Researchers can develop an ecological history by analyzing microfossils from different locations and times. A case study is included from a Miocene diatomite deposit paleolake from Northern Nevada. The method resulted in the extraction and isolation of Miocene microfossils dated to approximately 10.3 Mya including phytoliths and diatoms. Another application of this method includes the development of environmental interpretations and hypotheses regarding the future of modern vegetation.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

Remove centrifuge buckets and inserts daily to wash with a brush and warm soapy water. Wipe down the interior of the centrifuge with a moist paper towel.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}

This should be done in a dust collector or a fumehood with a protective surface (e.g. aluminum foil) laid down to protect the researchers and sample.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"d54o3","text":"Prepare sediment block by cleaning the exposed sections. Stratigraphical layers should be visible for best sampling strategy as per next steps.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ekun0","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"euene","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":[],"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"1lkl","text":"Here, our samples have layers/laminations. These layers can be separated to achieve finer stratigraphical resolution.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"8eg7i","text":"Determine how thick the sampling region should be in relation to the thickness of the geological layers. If the source specimen is densely layered, then a thinner sampling region will result in a higher accuracy of placing microfossils within correct historical timelines.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"gtk5","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a1gic","text":"E.g.: varve sediments (such as the examples included here) will include years of deposition in just a few centimeters. In contrast, metamorphic samples might include single-event deposition throughout meters of stratigraphy.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"937rs","text":"Use a flat tool to separate the sample from the rock. A flat chisel can separate portions until the whole sub-sample is isolated.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e0rrp","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"d5a1a","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7tork","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"5602ACBB644C11ED86F20A58A9FEAC02","height":364.87272727272733,"id":315463,"is_video":false,"legend":{"blocks":[{"data":[],"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"98fte","text":"Image 1: example sample of first chiseled sub-sample (composed of several layers) removed. Removed layer is approximately 0.5cm in depth.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":[]},"mime":"image/png","nestedSelector":null,"original_name":"diatomite slab.png","placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwcjbxh47.jpg","shadow":true,"source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwchbxh47.jpg","webp_placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwcibxh47.webp","webp_source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwcgbxh47.webp","width":580}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"sok2","text":"Mass the sample.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6b756","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"86dvp","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":[],"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"7ul0b","text":"Make sure to maintain equal mass across sub-samples throughout separation. Depending on the material sampled the mass will vary (e.g. diatomite achieved good microfossil density at 0.5g). For optimal results maintain an accuracy of ±0.05g.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"eiinr","text":"Repeat steps 1.2-1.4 for each sample while cleaning the tools and using new aluminum foil to prevent cross-contamination.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":7,"length":13}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"dsfv3","text":"Transfer each sample into a new plastic sealable bag, and then put that bag into a 2nd new plastic sealable bag.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"e1620","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"433h2","text":"Familiarize yourself with SDS (Safety Data Sheet) and follow the storage requirements of each chemical.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"879mn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]},{"key":"e822q","text":"Some reactions, including ZnBr2 in H2O, HCl to remove carbonates, and H2O2 to remove organics, may be vigorous with heat production, bubble formation, etc.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sub","offset":30,"length":1},{"style":"sub","offset":36,"length":1},{"style":"sub","offset":71,"length":1},{"style":"sub","offset":73,"length":2}],"entityRanges":[],"data":[]}],"entityMap":{}}
